    THIS FILE'S ROLE IN THE OVERALL POC
    ===================================
    This report is the lifecycle-distribution bar chart shown on the
    Manager View dashboard
    (../dashboards/pa_dashboards_x_[scope]_manager_view.xml). It sits
    alongside four other widgets to give a manager a complete operational
    picture of the team's case portfolio:

      - THIS bar chart shows the DISTRIBUTION of all cases across the
        six lifecycle states (Draft, Open, In Progress, Pending,
        Resolved, Closed) - the lifecycle-stage view. Managers use it
        to assess where cases pile up: a top-heavy Open/In Progress
        distribution signals intake-throughput backlog; a top-heavy
        Pending distribution signals dependency-blocking; a healthy
        funnel-shape distribution (Open > In Progress > Resolved >
        Closed) signals normal flow.
      - "All Cases by Type" donut/pie chart
        (../reports/x_[scope]_all_cases_by_type.xml) shows the
        SUBDOMAIN MIX between General Inquiry and Complaint -
        case-handling-pipeline view.
      - "All Cases by Priority" bar chart
        (../reports/x_[scope]_all_cases_by_priority.xml) shows the
        DISTRIBUTION across urgency tiers (Low, Medium, High, Critical) -
        urgency-tier view.
      - "Average Time to Close" single-score widget
        (../reports/x_[scope]_avg_time_to_close.xml) shows the
        operational throughput KPI.
      - "Cases Opened in Last 30 Days" single-score widget
        (../reports/x_[scope]_cases_opened_30d.xml) shows the
        intake-volume KPI.

    Together the five widgets satisfy the Manager View dashboard goal
    per AAP Section 0.4.4: "demonstrate that a case_manager ... see
    operationally relevant aggregate views on day one".

    SEMANTIC SOURCE-SIDE ANCHOR (READ-ONLY, NOT BYTE-FOR-BYTE PORTED)
    =================================================================
    The semantic ancestors of this report in the existing ArkCase
    codebase are two Java artifacts in the case-file-plugin:

      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/
        java/com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/CaseFile.java
        Lines 141-142:
            @Column(name = "cm_case_status")
            private String status;
        ArkCase tracked case status as a free-form String column on the
        `acm_case_file` MySQL table. Default value is "DRAFT" set in
        @PrePersist (line 312: setStatus("DRAFT")) when status is null.
        The CaseFileQueueHandler pipeline pre-save handler then promotes
        the status to "ACTIVE" when assigned to a queue. The ServiceNow
        target normalizes this to a Choice field with six explicit
        values per AAP Section 0.5.7 (Draft, Open, In Progress, Pending,
        Resolved, Closed) defined in ../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml
        and constrained to the transition matrix in AAP Section 0.5.5.
        The <group_by>status</group_by> below references this Choice
        field by element name; the bar chart renders one bar per
        distinct Choice label.

      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/
        java/com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/CaseByStatusDto.java
        Lines 33-57:
            public class CaseByStatusDto {
                private String status;
                private int    count;
                ... getters and setters ...
            }
        The (key, count) DTO that ArkCase produced for status-aggregation
        reports - precisely the (status, count) tuple shape this
        ServiceNow report produces natively via GlideAggregate. The
        Pentaho-rendered status bar chart in ArkCase consumed a
        List<CaseByStatusDto>; the ServiceNow target replaces this
        DTO + Pentaho pipeline with a native sys_report whose
        `<group_by>status</group_by>` plus `<aggregate>COUNT</aggregate>`
        produce the same tuple shape directly via the platform's
        GlideAggregate engine - no DTO, no external BI tool, no Solr
        facet. The dashboard widget renders the (status, count) pairs
        as bars.

      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/
        java/com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/
        CaseSummaryByStatusAndTimePeriodDto.java:
            private String                  timePeriod;
            private List<CaseByStatusDto>   caseByStatusDtoList;
        ArkCase aggregated cases by status across time periods using
        custom DTOs consumed by Pentaho BI reports. The aggregator was
        Pentaho-side, NOT JPA-side. The ServiceNow target replaces
        Pentaho-driven dimensional aggregation with platform-native
        sys_report records (this file plus the seven sibling reports
        in this folder), all powered by ServiceNow's native
        GlideAggregate engine instead of an external BI engine - per
        AAP Section 0.1.2 ("Reporting transformation: Pentaho BI +
        Solr aggregates -> ServiceNow Reports + Performance Analytics-
        style dashboards").

    DESIGN DECISIONS LOCKED IN BY THIS FILE
    =======================================
      - Aggregation discipline (AAP Section 0.5.1, this report's row):
        type = bar. Per agent-prompt Mandatory Field Specification,
        chart-type reports populate <type>, <group_by>, and <aggregate>;
        they leave <field_list/> and <aggregation_source/> empty. The
        rendered output is one vertical-bar chart with one bar per
        distinct value of `status`.

      - Group-by discipline (agent-prompt Rule 4 verbatim):
        <group_by>status</group_by>. The Choice field defined in
        ../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_status.xml. The six bars correspond
        to the six Choice values defined in
        ../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml: Draft, Open, In Progress,
        Pending, Resolved, Closed (Title Case, "In Progress" with single
        ASCII space - NOT "InProgress", NOT "in_progress", NOT
        "IN PROGRESS").

      - Filter discipline (agent-prompt Rule 5 verbatim):
        <filter/> empty. This report counts ALL cases regardless of
        status, priority, or assignment. The Manager View dashboard is
        intentionally an unfiltered aggregate-perspective view -
        per-viewer filtering belongs to Agent Workspace's "My Open
        Cases" list (../reports/x_[scope]_my_open_cases.xml) and
        "My Overdue Tasks" list (../reports/x_[scope]_my_overdue_tasks.xml).
        Note: x_[scope]_my_open_cases.xml DOES filter out Resolved/Closed
        because it serves an operational queue purpose, but THIS report
        retains Closed cases because the Manager View needs visibility
        into terminal-state volume to assess case throughput.

      - Aggregation discipline (agent-prompt Rule 6 verbatim):
        <aggregate>COUNT</aggregate>. Counts records per status bucket.
        <aggregation_source/> empty (COUNT does not require a numeric
        source field; it counts rows, not values).

      - Field-list discipline (agent-prompt Rule 9 verbatim):
        <field_list/> empty. Chart reports do NOT specify a field list;
        the field list is meaningful only for `type=list` reports per
        the sibling pattern in ../reports/x_[scope]_my_open_cases.xml
        (which uses <field_list>number,subject,priority,status,opened_date</field_list>).
        For chart reports, the chart-type and group-by fully determine
        what is rendered.

      - Per-viewer semantics: this report does NOT reference any
        user-specific identity (e.g., gs.getUserID()); it returns the
        SAME aggregated counts for every viewer. Therefore:
          1) The platform does not need to re-compute the aggregate
             per-user, only per-cache-cycle. <is_real_time>false</is_real_time>
             below permits cached evaluation.
          2) Different roles see the same numbers (modulo what their
             ACL permits them to read). For a `case_viewer`, all six
             bars appear (read-all ACL). For a `case_agent`, only
             bars for cases assigned to them or their group appear
             (assigned-only ACL per AAP Section 0.5.6). For a
             `case_manager`, all six bars appear (full ACL). The Manager
             View dashboard is gated to `case_manager` per AAP Section
             0.4.4, so the typical viewer sees the full team picture.

      - Why "type=bar" not "type=pie": per AAP Section 0.4.4 the Manager
        View dashboard pairs different chart types to different
        cardinalities of categorical data:
          - Status (6 buckets): bar chart - magnitude comparison
            across many discrete buckets favors absolute-count
            readability. The eye reads vertical bars left-to-right
            against a common baseline more accurately than radial
            slices when N >= 5 buckets. The same data is ALSO rendered
            on the Agent Workspace dashboard as a donut/pie via
            ../reports/x_[scope]_case_count_by_status.xml because at-a-
            glance proportional readability is more important for an
            individual contributor's morning-coffee dashboard than
            absolute-count comparison.
          - Priority (4 buckets): bar chart - same rationale at lower
            cardinality; ordinal urgency tiers benefit from left-to-
            right linear ordering.
          - Type (2 buckets, extensible): donut/pie chart -
            proportion comparison across a small number of buckets
            favors "what percentage is each?" readability.
        The deliberate diversity of chart types is a UX-quality
        decision per AAP Section 0.4.4 and is NOT to be flattened
        into "all bar" or "all pie" for consistency.

      - Why this report co-exists with x_[scope]_case_count_by_status.xml:
        per AAP Section 0.4.4 widget inventory, the SAME aggregation
        (group by status, COUNT) appears on BOTH dashboards but with
        DIFFERENT chart types and DIFFERENT audiences:
          * Agent Workspace -> x_[scope]_case_count_by_status.xml
            (type=pie, donut rendering) - quick visual proportion
            check for the agent's morning standup.
          * Manager View -> THIS file x_[scope]_all_cases_by_status.xml
            (type=bar) - precise count comparison for the manager's
            operational review.
        The two reports are deliberately separate sys_report records,
        each bound to its respective dashboard widget by `name`. They
        share the underlying GlideAggregate query shape but render
        independently.

      - Cache discipline: <is_real_time>false</is_real_time>. The
        platform may cache the aggregated counts and refresh on a
        cycle (typically 5 minutes for the Reports module). For a
        POC dashboard with 10 demo cases this distinction is
        cosmetic; for a production case-management deployment with
        thousands of cases it materially affects dashboard load
        time. The default-off setting matches the sibling reports
        (../reports/x_[scope]_all_cases_by_type.xml,
         ../reports/x_[scope]_case_count_by_status.xml,
         ../reports/x_[scope]_my_open_cases.xml,
         ../reports/x_[scope]_avg_time_to_close.xml,
         ../reports/x_[scope]_cases_opened_30d.xml).

      - Chart-size discipline: <chart_size>medium</chart_size>. The
        platform-default rendering size for embedded dashboard widgets.
        Matches the sibling reports.

      - Scope binding: <sys_scope>x_[scope]</sys_scope> and
        <sys_package source="x_[scope]">x_[scope]</sys_package>
        bind THIS record to the same scoped-app row that the parent
        sys_app record (../app/sys_app/x_[scope]_case_management.xml)
        publishes via the sys_scope record at
        ../app/sys_scope/x_[scope].xml (where <name>x_[scope]</name>
        and <source>x_[scope]</source>). Cross-file consistency: the
        sibling reports (x_[scope]_all_cases_by_type.xml,
        x_[scope]_case_count_by_status.xml, x_[scope]_my_open_cases.xml,
        x_[scope]_my_overdue_tasks.xml, x_[scope]_avg_time_to_close.xml,
        x_[scope]_cases_opened_30d.xml) use identical scope-reference
        values, ensuring all reports resolve to the same sys_app row at
        preview time. Reference-by-name not reference-by-sys_id per AAP
        Section 0.7.2 (no hardcoded sys_ids constraint).

      - <sys_id> determinism: the value
        deeaca81d8626c9c2cc2974716efd08c is the lowercase MD5 of the
        canonical record name "x_[scope]_all_cases_by_status". This
        matches the convention documented in
        ../reports/x_[scope]_all_cases_by_type.xml lines 232-253
        (md5("x_[scope]_all_cases_by_type") = f35f0a22b19d6e5385538eb3febb1a84),
        ../reports/x_[scope]_case_count_by_status.xml lines 223-242
        (md5("x_[scope]_case_count_by_status") = 32ae52ab8735ea76587edee6130abc06),
        ../reports/x_[scope]_my_open_cases.xml lines 219-236
        (md5("x_[scope]_my_open_cases") = ee04fa982b136ad35c6fe1512826f6ab),
        ../reports/x_[scope]_avg_time_to_close.xml lines 233-247
        (md5("x_[scope]_avg_time_to_close") = 79fabb5f5754b629205b2382face3ebb),
        and ../reports/x_[scope]_cases_opened_30d.xml lines 71-84
        (md5("x_[scope]_cases_opened_30d") = 95b2127b026a92ba5e041a8d4d7277ec).
        Deterministic derivation makes the Update Set re-importable
        on a fresh PDI without sys_id collisions: re-importing the
        same XML on the same or any future PDI resolves the same
        sys_id and idempotently updates the same report row rather
        than creating a duplicate. This stability is REQUIRED because
        the Manager View dashboard
        (../dashboards/pa_dashboards_x_[scope]_manager_view.xml)
        references THIS report by `<name>x_[scope]_all_cases_by_status</name>`,
        and the dashboard widget binding must resolve consistently
        across re-imports.

